@node PURPOSE "1.1 Purpose"
@{u}1.1 Purpose@{uu}

        This program was written to allow me to make backup copys of
        the data in my Casio B.O.S.S. and to be able to reload this
        data.

        Copyright 1996 Vincent J. Herried.
@endnode

@node requirements "1.2 System Requirements"
@{u}1.2 System Requirements@{uu}

AMIGA:
        Any model Amiga with a working serial port.

        Any release of AmigaDos  V2.0 or above should work with this version
        of BOSS.


Casio BOSS:

        According to the documentation for my SF-5300B you should be able to
        use this program with most SF models.  The following models have been
        tested:

        SF-4600

        SF-7500         Amiga -> BOSS transfers have problems above 4800 Baud.
                        See @{"problems" link problems}

        SF-5300B


HARDWARE:

        You need a serial interface between the connector on your BOSS and your
        Amiga serial port.

        Sources:

                CASIO sells these adaptors with the software for either a peecee or 
                a Mac.  Check with stores that sell the BOSS.

                Traveling Software at
                18702 North Creek Parkway
                Bothell, WA 98011-9916
                Sold both the interface and software also.


        Build your own:

                On aminet see hard/misc/mcc040.lha.  Contained in this package
                There is an iff file with a schematic diagram of a simple hardware
                interface that shouldn't cost more than $20.00 US.

                Also on aminet see comm/misc/casio.lha.  This author has also built
                his own interface and I expect to see construction documentation
                soon.
@endnode


@node installation "2.1 Installation" 
@{u}2.1 Installation@{uu}
        Setup:

        After connecting your serial interface (see @{"system requirements" link requirements})   
        Set your BOSS to send and receive 8 bits no parity.
        Set the baud rate on your BOSS to as fast as it will go.
        The default for this program is 9600.

        Make sure that the 2.5 mm plug that fits into your BOSS is all the way in.
        My older interface from Traveling Software had a large handle on it
        which prevented it from being properly connected to my SF-5300B.


        more information:

        Read your BOSS owners manual!


@endnode

@node options "2.2 Command line options"
@{u}2.2 Command line options@{uu}
@endnode

@node problems "2.3 Problems"
@{u}2.3 Problems@{uu}

        Make sure the hardware communications parameters in your BOSS
        match those you are using for this program.


        If you have trouble sending data to your unit, try
        dropping the baud rate.  My older SF7500 unit just didn't
        want to sync up when the BAUD rate was set at 9600.
        It worked fine when running at 4800.


        You may get a message "unknown data type xxxx"
        This means that your BOSS has a data type my program doesn't
        understand.  It will still be able to backup and restore
        the information to your BOSS, it just dosen't know what kind of
        data it represents.

        If you get this message, you can figure out what kind of data it represents
        in several ways.  One way would be to tell your BOSS to send the amiga
        just one kind of data at a time, then watch for the error message.
        if you figure out what it represents, please send me a note.

        An example, my newer BOSS 5300B has 'TODO' entrys.  By transmitting
        just these TODO entrys, I figured them out and updated my program
        to recognize them.  

        Please help me expand this program with your
        email.


@{jright} 
    See also @{"future" link future} @{"author" link author}        
@endnode
    
@node protocol "3.1 BOSS protocol"
@{u}3.1 BOSS protocol@{uu}

        The serial I/O protocol is pretty simple.
        It is started by the side that wants to transmit data.


        1.  Poll state.

        data sender:

                transmit polling characters <CR LF>
                read response for about 0.5 seconds.
                if response is <XON> go to step 2.
                else if retry limit exceeded stop with error message.
                else goto 1.



        data receiver:

                read optionally if wait time exceeded, end with error message.
                if poll is detected, transmit <XON> go to data receiver part of
                step 2.



        2.  Data transfer state.

        data sender:

                send first/next block of data.
                read response.
                if character received is <!> end the transmition.
                if character received is <?> resend the block of data.
                if character received is <#> and more data to send, go to step 2.
                if no more data to send, transmit <!> and end.


        data receiver:

                read block of data and calculate checksum character.
                if memory is full, send <!> and end.
                if checksum in incorrect send <?> go to step 3.
                if checksum is ok, transmit <#> and go to step 3.



Notes:
        All of the data is converted to printable ascii.
        
        Each block of data is preceeded with a colon, a control word 
        and terminated with a checksum byte.

        The checksum is a single byte that is zero minus the sum of all the
        transmitted bytes except for the leading colon.
@endnode

